   "source": [
    "# 23. What are some ways to make your model more robust to outliers?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "2ed77a48",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Outliers can seriously skew model performance, so making your model robust to outliers is a common interview topic. The idea is either to handle the outliers in data or use models/techniques that are less sensitive to them.\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 1. Data-Level Techniques (Handle the outliers first)\n",
    "🔹 Detect and remove outliers\n",
    "Methods:\n",
    "IQR (Interquartile Range)\n",
    "Z-score\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Remove values beyond 1.5 × IQR\n",
    "🔹 Cap / Clip values (Winsorization)\n",
    "Replace extreme values with upper/lower limits\n",
    "✔️ Keeps data size intact\n",
    "🔹 Transform the data\n",
    "Apply transformations:\n",
    "Log transform\n",
    "Square root\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Reduces impact of extreme values\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Use robust scaling\n",
    "Instead of standard scaling, use:\n",
    "Median and IQR\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "RobustScaler\n",
    "✅ 2. Model-Level Techniques\n",
    "🔹 Use robust algorithms\n",
    "\n",
    "Some models are naturally less sensitive:\n",
    "\n",
    "Tree-based models (Decision Trees, Random Forest)\n",
    "Ensemble methods\n",
    "🔹 Use robust loss functions\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of squared error:\n",
    "\n",
    "MAE (L1 loss) → less sensitive to outliers\n",
    "Huber Loss → combination of L1 and L2\n",
    "🔹 Regularization\n",
    "Helps prevent model from overfitting to extreme values\n",
    "✅ 3. Feature Engineering\n",
    "Remove noisy or irrelevant features\n",
    "Create bins (binning reduces effect of extremes)\n",
    "✅ 4. Validation Techniques\n",
    "Use cross-validation\n",
    "Ensure outliers don’t dominate a single split\n",
    "🚀 Real-world Example\n",
    "Fraud detection → outliers may actually be important\n",
    "👉 Don’t blindly remove them—understand context\n",
    "🎯 Interview-Ready Answer (Short)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “To make models robust to outliers, we can use data preprocessing techniques like removing or capping outliers, applying transformations, and using robust scaling. At the model level, we can choose algorithms like tree-based models and use robust loss functions such as MAE or Huber loss.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Pro Tip\n",
    "\n",
    "Say this in interview 👇\n",
    "👉 “Outliers should not always be removed—they can carry important information depending on the problem.”\n",
    "\n",
    "If you want, I can give:\n",
    "\n",
    "Python code for outlier detection (IQR, Z-score)\n",
    "Interview case studies (when NOT to remove outliers)\n",
    "Comparison of L1 vs L2 loss (very commonly asked)"
   ]
  },
